Here's a minimal API endpoint that accepts multiple images plus a description field via `multipart/form-data`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.Features;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size to 50 MB
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (IFormFileCollection files, HttpRequest request) =>
{
    var description = request.Form["description"].ToString();

    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No files uploaded.");

    var allowed = new[] { "image/jpeg", "image/png", "image/gif", "image/webp" };
    var saved = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        if (!allowed.Contains(file.ContentType))
            return Results.BadRequest($"'{file.FileName}' is not an allowed image type.");

        var dest = Path.Combine("uploads", $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}");
        Directory.CreateDirectory("uploads");

        await using var stream = File.Create(dest);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream);
        saved.Add(dest);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new { description, uploadedFiles = saved });
})
.DisableAntiforgery()                    // needed if you're not sending an antiforgery token
.Accepts<IFormFileCollection>("multipart/form-data");

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **`IFormFileCollection`** binds all files from the form; the `description` text field is read from `request.Form`.
- **Kestrel's `MaxRequestBodySize`** defaults to ~28 MB — bump it to 50 MB explicitly.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** is required for minimal APIs accepting form data unless you're sending the token.
- Validate `ContentType` server-side — never trust the extension alone.

**Example `curl` call:**

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "files=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "files=@photo2.png" \
  -F "description=Vacation photos"
```

If you're behind IIS/reverse proxy, also set the limit there (e.g., `web.config` `maxAllowedContentLength`).
